02/28/2023,748.303(a)(12)(A) - Individual Standards Evaluated,Individual Standards Evaluated,No,05/31/2023,06/16/2023,Individual Standards Evaluated,Medium High,Yes,A child's suicide attempt was not reported as required by minimum standards. ,"During the inspection it was discussed staff members are being trained on when to report a serious incident versus when to document a minor incident. Posts were observed in the units describing what needs to be reported to CCR.

All suicide attempts are deemed as urgent and accessed as priory level one (1) at Fort Behavioral Health with the following actions taken:
Â	The client is immediately placed with a staff on duty, avoiding any addition attempts to self- harm. The assigned staff remains with the client, ensuring safety and supervision. 
Â	Medical Assessment (conducted by the nurse on duty).
Â	A Columbia Assessment is conducted (All Staff is trained to conduct the assessment). The Columbia Assessment is located under the Clinical Assessment in KIPU.
Â	Room search, ensuring there are no items hidden or self-made that can be utilized to carry out a plan to self-harmÂroom is deemed and reported as safe prior to the client returning.
Â	Hotline Call /Report For ALL SUICIDE ATTEMPTS, which will state the date / time of the calls, Name and ID # from Intake / Report number, all of which is documented in the clients file / chart in KIPU. 
Â	Notification to the guardian listed on file, located in KIPU.
Â	Notification to the therapist regarding a client follow-up.
Â	Continuous Care: The advised (doctors) orders are followed ensuring that safety and supervision is met.
Â	 Continuous Care: After the Clinical Assessments or /and changes in the Doctors Orders (if required) the client remains on Close Monitored Supervision.
Â	Continuous Care: All Managers / Leads are required to conduct a walkthrough before and after each shiftÂNotification required.
Safety Plans:
Â	All Safety Plans are and will be adjusted throughout the stay of each client until discharged (d/c) from the facility, which include doctorÂs orders and changes that range as followed: q5, q15, and 1:1 supervision. 
Orders that indicate 1:1 during wake hours, the sleep hours consist of staff positioned at the doorway of clients assigned sleeping area, ensuring that safety and supervision is carried outÂThis method can be advised by the LCCA, or and the AOC (Administrator On Call). 
Method of Communication:
Â	The notification and communication methods of these changes are provided to the staff employed at Fort Behavioral Health include both via Teams and Shift Reports, as well as a DIRECT ORDER (documented) from Administration, ensuring that the proper rounds are being conducted for the safety of the client. 

In closing, Fort Behavioral Health will continue to conduct the required trainings to all staff working with clients that are in care / treatment until discharged, ensuring that safety and supervision is provided under the rules of Minimum Standards. In addition, staff will continue to conduct rounds that are set forth or / and recommend within the Safety Plan, catering to needs of each client and made aware of any / all changes.
All staff will continue to be briefed on the history and made aware of all precautionary measures recommended upon intake, as well as a review / refresher on trauma and triggers during shift reports.
Fort Behavioral Health with continue to supervise, monitor, review, and train each staff placed on a Performance Improvement Plan (PIP), ensuring that the conditions are met under the rules and guidelines for Minimum Standards. 
Fort Behavioral Health will continue to improve with great efforts with a Continuous Plan of Care for each client, adhering to Policy changes under the rules and guidelines for Minimum Standards. 
